results.title: Prince of Wales: LiDAR and The Tatoosh School
results.description: This map displays areas in which airborne LiDAR scans were taken within the Tongass National Forest on Prince of Wales Island from 2017 to 2018 for the use of The Nature Conservancy, the United States Forest Service, and the United States Geological Survey. Additionally, this map displays the regular driving route for The Tatoosh School Field Ecology course in 2018. The Tongass National Forest feature layer, LiDAR Acquisition Area feature layer, and Southeast Alaska towns feature layer were obtained from carson.hauck@tnc.org_TNC. The total LiDAR Acquisition Area 2017-2018 feature layer was created by merging the LiDAR Acquisition Area 2017 feature layer and the LiDAR Acquisition Area 2018 feature layer.
results.snippet: Areas in which airborne LiDAR scans were taken within the Tongass National Forest on Prince of Wales Island from 2017 to 2018. Also displayed is the regular driving route for The Tatoosh School Field Ecology course in 2018.

results.title: Black footed ferret Reintroduction Project
results.description: It is a map display the Black-footed ferret Reintroduction area in Northeast Colorado. All the green area is the suitable area which contains criteria: in their food range (Black-Tail Prairie dog), contiguous grassland areas lager than 10,000 acres and away from disturbance. The three dark green areas mean the three largest reintroduction area in northeast of Colorado. The map is used to give some suggestions for Black-footed ferret reintroduction project for Colorado Department of Parks and Wildlife.

A variety of data capture techniques were used including drawing on mylar overlays at 1:50,000 scale USGS county mapsheets and implementation of the SmartBoard Interactive Whiteboard using stand-up, real-time digitizing at various scales (Cowardin, M., M. Flenner. March 2003. Maximizing Mapping Resources. GeoWorld 16(3):32-35).

results.licenseInfo: This wildlife distribution map is a product and property of Colorado Parks and Wildlife, a division of the Colorado Department of Natural Resources. Care should be taken in interpreting these data. Written documents may accompany this map and should be referenced. The information portrayed on these maps should not replace field studies necessary for more localized planning efforts. The data are gathered at a variety of scales; discrepancies may become apparent at larger scales. The areas portrayed here are graphic representations of phenomena that are difficult to reduce to two dimensions. Animal distributions are fluid; animal populations and their habitats are dynamic.

results.title: Mushroom Foraging in Cameron Peak Wildfire
results.description:
An analysis of common environments and conditions mushrooms can be found growing. Using this map, one can know where prime foraging locations are within the Cameron Peak Wildfire burn area. 

*This serves as a tool to yield success in a foraging trip, the areas stated as "Ideal" are not a guaranteed place to find mushrooms.
results.snippet: This is a short guide with included map for ideal edible mushroom foraging in the burn area of the Cameron Peak Wildfire.
results.accessInformation:
DEM for Cameron Peak fire Area:
USGS National Map, 'USGS_13_n41w106.tif'

﻿Flowlines for both Cache La Poudre and Big Thompson Rivers:
USGS National Hydrography Dataset (NHD) 'NHD_H_10190007_HU8_GDB.gdb'

Cache La Poudre River Shapefile:
Colorado State University Geospatial Centroid 'CLP_streams100k-shp.zip'

Cameron Peak Burn Severity and Area:
BAER https://services1.arcgis.com/KNdRU5cN6ENqCTjk/arcgis/rest/services/Cameron_Peak_Fire_Soil_Burn_Severity/FeatureServer/0

Cover Image:
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/Black_Morel.jpg

Colorado Burn Areas and Mushroom Foraging Information:
https://www.modern-forager.com/summer-morels-and-high-altitudes-in-colorado/

Recent information Regarding Black Morel Foraging in Colorado:
https://www.modern-forager.com/colorado-burn-morel-2019-update/

results.title: Dam Impacts on PNW Salmon Habitat
results.description: A map showing critical Chinook, Sockeye, Coho, and Chum salmon habitat in the Pacific Northwest designated under the Endangered Species Act. Lock and dam systems and reservoirs alter the waterways that salmon rely on for reproductive habitat and migration. Efforts that have been made to aid salmon with migration include fish ladders and even the removal of dams that were decommissioned or were no longer economically feasible to maintain. Some content requires zooming to view.
results.snippet: A map showing critical habitat of four salmon species in the Pacific Northwest designated under the Endangered Species Act, as well as Columbia Basin water and fish facilities that may have an impact on wild salmon habitat and migration.
results.accessInformation: Data used from Esri and PSMFC GIS (Admin)

results.title: Oklahoma Injection Wells and Earthquakes
results.description: This map contains heat density of earthquakes in Oklahoma from 2000 to 2018. Injection wells, a known cause for an increase in earthquakes in Oklahoma, are also shown. Faults are shown for comparison as well. This map also contains municipalities to show the impact of the earthquakes. Earthquakes and municipalities are labeled on a zoomed-in level. Pop-ups are included for earthquakes, injection wells, and municipalities.
results.snippet: Heat map of earthquakes relative to injection wells in Oklahoma.

results.title: Analysis quick lesson invasive weeds - Barker K
results.description:
This map shows the range of Nassella Tussock and the location of campgrounds in New Zealand.  This map can be used to determine which campgrounds should take steps to reduce interactions with Nassella Tussock in order to reduce the spread of the invasive weed.  The Create Buffers, Find Existing Locations, and Summarize Within tools can be used for this analysis.

This map and its accompanying workflow were created for instructional purposes only and should not be used as an authoritative resource.

results.title: Coral Bleaching
results.description: This map shows the effects of coral bleaching on worldwide reefs. Layers include reef areas, sampling stations, locations of artificial reefs, areas where mass bleaching events have already happened, and areas at risk for bleaching events. By viewing this map, I hope that others will understand the magnitude of the threat that our reefs are facing, and the how severe the overall threat of global warming. Because of increased water temperatures, corals lose the vital algae they rely on for protection and a food source. Without them, they are left weak and vulnerable, and die majority of the time. Coral reefs directly contribute the the health of our oceans and our planet, and it is imperative that action is quickly taken to halt contributions to climate change. This is just one of the countless impacts of climate change around the world, and it is our job to fix it.
results.snippet: This map shows the effect of coral bleaching on worldwide reefs.
results.accessInformation: National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), NOAA Coral Reef Watch Program, MarineCadastre.gov, National Ocean Service (NOS), Office for Coastal Management (OCM), The Nature Conservancy
